{
  "text": "Excitability in hippocampal CA1 dendrites critically depends on rapidly activating and inactivating, A-type K \u03e9 channels. In addition to controlling action potential (AP) backpropagation into dendrites [CITATION_1] , these channels contribute to synaptic integration [CITATION_2] . Kv4.2 channels, which produce the A-current in CA1 dendrites [CITATION_3] , are trafficked out of the membrane upon the induction of long-term potentiation (LTP), a form of synaptic plasticity [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] ). In addition to inducing a lasting increase in synaptic strength, LTP also results in an increase in the excitability of CA1 neurons [CITATION_6] . This \"intrinsic plasticity\" likely involves changes in the function of a number of voltage-gated channels, including Kv4.2 [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] ). The specific mechanisms involved with regulating Kv4.2 expression upon LTP induction are unknown but acute activation of protein kinase A (PKA) leads to an increase in dendritic excitability through a downregulation of A-type K \u03e9 currents in CA1 dendrites [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] and a decrease in Kv4.2 surface expression in hippocampal neurons, which requires PKA phosphorylation at Kv4.2 site S552 [CITATION_13] . We therefore hypothesized that Kv4.2 may be associated with A-kinase-anchoring protein (AKAP) complexes which provide restricted, local PKA signaling.",
  "correct_citation": {
